rect.title: The production of emf across an electrical conductor in a changing magnetic field.
Magnetic flux is defined as the product of an area and the component of the magnetic flux density perpendicular to that area.
Magnetic flux linkage, ,in a coil with N-turns is defined as the product of the magnetic flux passing through a coil and the number of turns of the coil.
Faradays law states that the magnitude of the induced e.m.f. in a coil is directly proportional to the rate of change of the magnetic flux linking (or cutting) the coil.
Lenzs Law states that the direction of the induced e.m.f. is such that its effects oppose the change which causes it.

The changing current in the primary coil gives rise to a changing flux in the core. As the flux links with the secondary coil, there is changing flux in the secondary coil. By Faradays Law, an e.m.f. is induced in the secondary coil.
When bulk pieces of metal are moving in a magnetic field, or are exposed to a changing magnetic field, loops of electrical currents are induced in the metal
